g African Americans.","English and Scottish: from the rare Middle English personal name <i>Scot</i> (Old English <i>Scott</i>, possibly also Old Norse <i>Skotr</i>), only certainly attested in northern England.","English: variant of   Scutt  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Scutt","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Pierre.","Americanized form of Dutch   Schutte   ‘archer’.","English: nickname for a short person, from Middle English <i>scut(e)</i> ‘short’, or else for a swift runner, from Middle English <i>scut</i> ‘hare’."]}]},{"name":"Jeanette","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jeannette  , in the 1920s and 30s associated particularly with the Americam singer and film star  Jeanette MacDonald  (  1902–65 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Jeannette","meanings":["diminutive form of <i>Jeanne</i>, feminine form of <i>Jean</i> ‘John’, now also used in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":37,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705202,"age":46,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1